definition:
*Dirichlet’s function* $f:\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}$ is defined as
$$f\left(x\right) =
  \left\{ 
  \begin{array}{ll} 
    \frac{1}{q}  &  \textrm{if } x=\frac{p}{q}
                        \textrm{ is a rational number in lowest terms,} \\
    0              &  \textrm{if } x \textrm{ is an irrational number.} 
  \end{array}
  \right.$$ This function has the property that it is continuous at
every irrational number and discontinuous at every rational one.

Another function that often goes by the same name is the function
$$f\left(x\right) =
  \left\{ 
  \begin{array}{ll} 
    1  &  \textrm{if } x \textrm{ is an rational number.}\\
    0              &  \textrm{if } x \textrm{ is an irrational number.} 
  \end{array}
  \right.$$ This nowhere-continuous function has the surprising
expression $$\begin{aligned}
f(x) = \lim_{m \to \infty} \lim_{n \to \infty} \cos^{2 n} (m! \pi x).\end{aligned}$$

This is often given as the (amazing!) example of a sequence of
everywhere-continuous functions whose limit function is nowhere
continuous.
